9 ff. Note how skillfully Horace introduces these complimentary allusions to Pollio's other literary attainments. — paulum: for a little: z'.e. until the history shall be finished. —- severae: solemn. — desit: the public will miss the tragedies. — theatris: with the plural, cf. 1, 2, 15 f. This is not

proof that Pollio's plays were acted3 they were probably in- tended to be read.

11 f. ordinaris: set in order, tle. have arranged the details of thy work. — repetes: thou skalt re- sume thy glorians task (grande munus).—cecr0pio coturno : the high buskin (cothurnus) was worn by actors in tragedy, the low slipper (soccus) in comedy. The adjective cecropio is appropriate, as Athens was the place where tragedy came to its highest perfectiori.

13 f. praesidium . . . reis: eight of the nine titles of Pollio's speeches are for the defense. This verse was probably in Ovid's mind when he wrote of Germanicus Fasti 1, 22 civica pro trepides cum tulit arma reis. —consulenti: in its deliberativas. The phrase in- signe praesidium is still applicable here, as Pollio's advice was a de- fense to the welfare of the state.
